I found this game on sale, and even though I am not much of a motorsport/racing fan, I decided to give it a try based on the reviews. I am so glad I did - this is one of the best executed and entertaining games I have played on Android!  It has enough tutorial/tool-tips to introduce the gameplay and interface to a new player, but doesn't completely hold your hand. There is a lot of complexity to the game, but at the same time it isn't too intimidating. The attention to detail, from the graphics to the in-game social media posts, really sucks you into the sport. I have a hard time putting it down and frequently find myself in a loop of, "just one more race" or "I'll go to bed as soon as my engineers finish building this new suspension!"

It's really well rounded manager sim. It gives you a great initial 
challenge but after you begin to catch up the top teams the difficulty 
drops significantly for a couple of reasons. First of all the AI simply 
can't keep up with the race pace and even the top teams do some really 
questionable decisions in the race with the tyre choices for instance. Tyre 
wear is the only real way to strategise in the race, but it doesn't work as 
intended as fuel doesn't affect the cars whatsoever. (except makes the pit 
stop a bit longer) so the only valid strategy is to use softest tyres and 
go full steam ahead. Car with harder tyres and longer stints is bound to 
lose because the car exiting the pits with soft tyres is faster than the 
ones around the track, even though it should weigh more and thus run 
slower. It's a great game nonetheless and provides a couple days of fun for 
anyone really. Hope they will go a bit more in depth with the future 
updates.

A great game. Had fun with it. However, there are hidden pay walls after you get promoted for the first time. If you go on a negative balance for more than three races you are forced to either pay real money to get funds or fire team members.  After you get promoted it's very easy to go bankrupt. I farmed 5-6 seasons on the first tier just to increase my stats and prepare for the higher requirements. After I got promoted, I was dominating the second tier but went bankrupt on the last 2 races as there is no real income other than sponsors, which are way too random in what they offer you.   So after I went bankrupt I lost both my best drivers which I invested from the start of the game. Basically, as the game moves on your expenses increase but not your income. Success has nothing to do with your income either.  I am forced to quit as I lost my progress due to bad game mechanics designed to make you pay to keep playing.  Bottom line, this is already a paid app. I understand that you want to have some income as a company, but the pay walls are a really bad user experience. I would gladly get back in the game if something is done about this. I really enjoyed the first title and also the PC version. But this is not what I expected from the sequel.

After playing the first Motorsport Manager, I am pleased and impressed with the depth and detail MM2 has built on top of the original. The added features adds a much more difficult and addicting spin on the game.  Now that I can see what extent you are able to push this platform of this game, I must highly suggest an endurance (IMSA, WEC, ELMS) variant. You could introduce within each race something next level, multi-class racing with multiple driver changes. Sprint and long distances races with set up changes.   The development program could be quite long as well. Start at low level multi class, ST and GT4, Move to GT4 and GT3, into GT3 and P2 or P1, possibly a P2 and P1. Start in ST and move up. Have 2 to 4 manufacturers in each class, whether licensed or made up and that would be a big step forward.   Thank you for the game it is quite fun and addicting.

If you've played Motorsport Manager at the beginning you would have thought they weren't going to expand upon it. Or that it wasn't possible, until they made a PC version of Motorsport Manager.  I bought into the hype of the PC version and immediately fell in love with what they did there and how improved it was. But something was missing.  Something smaller..... It appears as though Playsport had the same thought. Lugging a large computer through the city won't work.  So Motorsport Manager 2 hit the market. They took the entire PC version, simplified the calendar, simplified the cars, shrunk graphics but kept the game as updated as the PC version to show improvements from MM1 to MM2.  This is a complete game and with how they developed the PC version in mind. I hope to see continual improvement for atleast another year or 2.  Thanks Christian West and Playsport Games. (Oh and Sega too)

While a definite improvement on the first MM there are a few aspects that could use improvement. My biggest complaint is that the UI/UX has not been designed for mobile use. This is very clearly a port of the PC version. I miss the mobile friendly buttons, UI, and vertical perspective of MM 1 that made playing with one hand a breeze. (with small children two hands aren't always available - I type this with a sleeping toddler occupying my left arm/hand) This horizontal perspective isn't necessary... It's a display of non-existent UI/UX design. Hopefully the devs will read this and take legitimate feedback from a fellow game designer and improve the mobile UX.   While a UI overhaul/vertical perspective is likely out of the question since they've already launched, a couple smaller improvements could go a long way: 1) Description/Tool tip texts are way too small for a mobile version. I'm playing on an S7 and struggle to read a lot of the text without the phone a few inches from my face. Font should be legible at a casual distance. (45-60cm viewing distance)  2) A number of clickable areas, such as the drivers racing strategy (a very major component) are extremely small and easily missed.   Overall, I love the game. The mobile execution is just really lacking. After such a strong showing from its predecessor, it's a shame that the same love for mobile isn't present in this much deeper and improved gameplay experience.   It just doesn't seem to have been designed for mobile.
